SIMPLE: ustulation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ustulation
<hw>Us`tu*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>ustulation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of burning or searing.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W. Petty.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>The operation of expelling
one substance from another by heat, as sulphur or arsenic from ores, in
a muffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Pharm.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The roasting or
drying of moist substances so as prepare them for pulverizing.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The burning of wine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Lascivious passion; concupiscence.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not certain that they took the better part when they chose
<qex>ustulation</qex> before marriage, expressly against the
apostle.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Usual</ent>⟦br⟧
